      "text": "ERCOT - Wind generation passes Coal for first time in 2020 | Energy Central [Skip to content](#content)\nPart of**[Energy & Sustainability Network](https://energycentral.com/c/ecn)**»\n![](https://energycentral.com/sites/default/files/styles/original_webp/public/ece/nodes/264334/energy-collective-group-header-image-240x240.jpg?itok=hYoXBUtN)\n## [The Energy Collective Group](https://energycentral.com/c/ec)**\nThis group brings together the best thinkers on energy and climate. Join us for smart, insightful posts and conversations about where the energy industry is and where it is going.\n[Join](https://energycentral.com/c/ec/ercot-wind-generation-passes-coal-first-time-2020)\n* [Home](https://energycentral.com/c/ec)\n* [Posts](https://energycentral.com/c/ec/stream)\n* [Q&A](https://energycentral.com/c/ec/qa)\n* [Calendar](https://energycentral.com/c/ec/calendar)\n* [News](https://energycentral.com/c/ec/news)\n* [Members](https://energycentral.com/c/ec/members)\n* [Experts](https://energycentral.com/c/ec/experts)\n* [Sponsors](https://energycentral.com/c/ec/sponsors)\n**Post**\n# ERCOT - Wind generation passes Coal for first time in 2020\n![Joe Deely&#039;s picture](https://energycentral.com/sites/default/files/styles/thumbnail/public/pictures/picture-207031-1685900989.jpg?itok=KkIv6lsS \"Joe Deely's picture\")\n[Joe Deely](https://energycentral.com/member/profile/joe-deely-0)[37,676](https://energycentral.com/members/reputation)\nDirector,Mission City Research\nStarting a non-profit that is focused on clean energy jobs in the US.\n* Member since 2018\n* 1,990 items added with 272,171 views\n[Contact](https://energycentral.com/messages/send/207031)\nFollow\n[Profile](https://energycentral.com/member/profile/joe-deely-0)\n* * [Like(1)](https://energycentral.com/user/login)\n* [Comment(7)](#ece-comments)\n* Jan 17, 2021Jan 17, 2021 10:24 pm GMT\n* 1831 views\nERCOT recently released its[full 2020 set of generation data](http://www.ercot.com/content/wcm/lists/197392/DemandandEnergy2020.xlsx).\n![](https://energycentral.com/sites/default/files/users/207031/Ecot%20fuel%20share.jpg)\nFor the first time,**total wind generation surpassed coal generation**. A 10.4TWh increase in wind generation along with a 9.3TWh decrease in coal assured that wind is now far ahead of coal and pulling away. Strong growth in solar generation meant that NG generation also declined in 2020 - particularly simple cycle generation.  Great news all-around.\nWind capacity is forecasted to grow by another 4GW(about 14%) in 2021and solar is forecasted to grow by over 6GW(150%) in 2021. The continued strong \"teamwork\" between these two sources means that the**zero-carbon share of electricity generation**in Texas will continue to grow.\nWhen will solar generation pass coal generation for a full year?\n![](https://energycentral.com/sites/default/files/users/207031/ERCOT%20Zero%20Carbon%20Fuel%20Share.jpg)\n* [solar-power](https://energycentral.com/topics/solar-power)\n* [wind-power](https://energycentral.com/topics/wind)\nJoe Deely\n###### Discussions\n### [Sign in to Participate](https://energycentral.com/user/login?destination=node/461284)\n[![Matt Chester's picture](https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/c2a12446c72c44cfd6ad5e2c22bad6e5.jpg?d=identicon&s=100&r=G \"Matt Chester's picture\")](https://energycentral.com/member/profile/matt-chester)\n[Matt Chester](https://energycentral.com/member/profile/matt-chester)on Jan 18, 2021\nLooks like 2019-2020 was the largest single year gain for solar-- while the Lonestar STate has embraced wind for a while, it's good to see solar finally seeing some investment (especially as wind/solar can work well in complementary fashion in terms of when they're generating)\n* [Sign in](https://energycentral.com/user/login?destination=node/461284#comment-form)or[Register](https://energycentral.com/user/register?destination=node/461284#comment-form)to post comments\n![Joe Deely's picture](https://energycentral.com/sites/default/files/styles/thumbnail/public/pictures/picture-207031-1685900989.jpg?itok=KkIv6lsS \"Joe Deely's picture\")\n[Joe Deely](https://energycentral.com/member/profile/joe-deely-0)on Jan 18, 2021\n> Looks like 2019-2020 was the largest single year gain for solar-- while the Lonestar STate has embraced wind for a while...\n> Exactly... below I have added an additional year to the chart. Wind has shown a pretty steady increase but solar has now exploded onto the scene. You can expect solar to more than doublegeneration in 2021 vs 2020.\nAlso note how quickly wind passed coal... Coal was ahead by 25TWh in 2018 and in just two years Wind is now ahead by 19 TWh. Two trains going in opposite directions.\n![](https://energycentral.com/sites/default/files/users/207031/ERCOT%20-%203%20years.jpg)\n* [Sign in](https://energycentral.com/user/login?destination=node/461284#comment-form)or[Register](https://energycentral.com/user/register?destination=node/461284#comment-form)to post comments\n![Nathan Wilson's picture](https://energycentral.com/sites/default/files/styles/thumbnail/public/pictures/56f9679c2a799.jpg?itok=9SwF-A6m \"Nathan Wilson's picture\")\n[Nathan Wilson](https://energycentral.com/member/profile/nathan-wilson-0)on Jan 18, 2021\n> \"... while the Lonestar STate has embraced wind for a while, it's good to see solar finally seeing some investment ...\"\n> That''s not necessarily good news. According to the latest data from DOE NREL, wind energy is still cheaper to build at large scale than solar PV (both have an installed cost around $1.3/Watt\\_AC in Texas, but windpower has a capacity factor that is much higher).\nA pivot from wind to (more expensive) solar could mean that developers believe that wind is hitting the point of diminishing cost effectiveness (that doesn''t mean it can''t keep growing, but it might require some sort of stronger policy support).\nThe latest report on the windpower marketfrom the Lawrence Berkeley National Labs supports this as well ([link](https://emp.lbl.gov/wind-technologies-market-report)):\n![Value of windpower-2020](https://i.imgur.com/H43hqYZ.png)\nNote: the green bars show the contribution of location, which could be addressed with improvement to transmission, but the blue profile (which just means, \"produces a lot when prices are low\") bars will be much more difficult to address.\n* [Sign in](https://energycentral.com/user/login?destination=node/461284#comment-form)or[Register](https://energycentral.com/user/register?destination=node/461284#comment-form)to post comments\n![Joe Deely's picture](https://energycentral.com/sites/default/files/styles/thumbnail/public/pictures/picture-207031-1685900989.jpg?itok=KkIv6lsS \"Joe Deely's picture\")\n[Joe Deely](https://energycentral.com/member/profile/joe-deely-0)on Jan 19, 2021\nWind generation has lowered prices in late afternoon/evening and demand is generally higher on ERCOT during the day. So yes, solar is definitely more valuable right now than wind on the ERCOT grid.\nThat said, as of[Nov 2020](http://www.ercot.com/content/wcm/lists/219848/Capacity_Changes_by_Fuel_Type_Charts_December_2020.xlsx)ERCOT had about 25 GW of wind capacity and it looks like another 10GW of wind capacity will be added over the next couple of years.\nThrow in all the solar generation that is being added and coal in TX is gonna be in a world of hurt. Expect to see a bunch of coal retirement announcementsin the mid 20s.\nWhat will that mean? With less coalthe \"\"value\"\" of wind will go up. More wind projects will \"\"pencil out\"\".\nNote: wewill also see a lot more longer-term storage being added to ERCOT.\nCurious - where did you get the \"\"latest data\"\" on NREL prices for solar? The only thing I could find was from 2018 - which of course for solar is old news. From what I can see, Solar in TX is now at or less than$1.0/Watt\\_AC.\n* [Sign in](https://energycentral.com/user/login?destination=node/461284#comment-form)or[Register](https://energycentral.com/user/register?destination=node/461284#comment-form)to post comments\n![Nathan Wilson's picture](https://energycentral.c",
